File: NPA head Shamila Batohi said law enforcement must be better equipped to win the battle against the corruption. JOHANNESBURG - The National Prosecuting Authority has received a cash injection for the establishment of an office where the public can lodge complaints. Germany has donated nearly R10-million to the NPA for the office. READ: NPA still investigating Steinhoff scandal Members of the public will be able to file complaints against staff, including prosecutors. NPA head Shamila Batohi has said law enforcement must be better equipped to win the battle against the corruption. The structure will be in Batohi's office with technical assistance from the Institute for Security Studies.